# **Patterns**

Patterns help us solve typical problems. Arch patterns deals with structure and responsibilities of the system parts. Design patterns deals with specific problems in code. Bonus \- improved ability to read, because another devs can understand what our code do and understand the parts of the system, easy to analyze the project.  
Core idea \- low coupling hi cohesion and SOC \- we should decouple logic from presentation.

**Data-fetching strategies**

* [Asynchronous State Handler](https://martinfowler.com/articles/data-fetch-spa.html#async-state-handler): Utilize custom hooks or composable APIs to abstract data fetching and state management away from your components. This pattern centralizes asynchronous logic, simplifying component design and enhancing reusability across your application.  
* [Fallback Markup](https://martinfowler.com/articles/data-fetch-spa.html#fallback-markup): React's enhanced Suspense model supports a more declarative approach to fetching data asynchronously, streamlining your codebase.  
* [Parallel Data Fetching](https://martinfowler.com/articles/data-fetch-spa.html#parallel-data-fetching): Maximize efficiency by fetching data in parallel, reducing wait times and boosting the responsiveness of your application.  
* [Code Splitting](https://martinfowler.com/articles/data-fetch-spa.html#code-splitting): Employ lazy loading for non-essential components during the initial load, leveraging Suspense for graceful handling of loading states and code splitting, thereby ensuring your application remains performant.  
* [Prefetching](https://martinfowler.com/articles/data-fetch-spa.html#prefetching): By preemptively loading data based on predicted user actions, you can achieve a smooth and fast user experience.

\*GRASP (General Responsibility Assignment Software Patterns) is a design pattern in object-oriented software development used to assign responsibilities for different modules of code. 

As a tool for software developers, GRASP provides a means to solve organizational problems and offers a common way to speak about abstract concepts. The design pattern sets responsibilities for objects and classes in object-oriented program design. 

GRASP with object-oriented programming classifies problems and their solutions together as patterns. With these problems and solutions well defined, they can be applied in other similar instances. GRASP assigns seven types of roles to classes and objects in order to make for clear delineation of responsibilities. 

These roles are: 

- Controller Information   
- Expert Creator   
- High Cohesion  
- Low Coupling   
- Polymorphism   
- Protected Classes 

![][image2]

GRASP is occasionally coupled with other design patterns such as SOLID. This combination makes for the convincing moniker of SOLID GRASP. Design patterns such as these help keep code simpler, more organized, more comprehensible, analyzable and reusable.
